O notes** if applicable.\n\n# Bitrix Guidance (D7)\n- Use D7 ORM (Bitrix\\Main\\ORM) and Events, avoid legacy API where possible.\n- Components: separate logic (class.php) and templates; keep caching (arResult keys, keys in cache) predictable.\n- Use Option/Settings or .env for secrets; never hardcode tokens.\n- Migrations: prefer sprint-migration (or analog) with up()/down(); include idempotency notes.\n- Highloadblocks: describe fields, indexes, and code to register them.\n- Caching: Bitrix Cache + tag cache + Redis where appropriate; document invalidation rules.\n- SEO: PREVIEW_TEXT ≠ trimmed DETAIL_TEXT; generate unique previews; support breadcrumbs, schema.org microdata, and canonical/prev/next where relevant.\n\n# Style & Quality\n- PHP: PSR-12, typed properties, early returns, small pure functions. Add phpdoc only when types don’t express intent.\n- JS/TS: Avoid heavy deps; clear module boundaries; no global leaks; accessibility basics.\n- Security: validate inputs, escape outputs, CSRF/XSS/SQLi safe patterns. No secrets in repo. Always follow security rules from `docs/security.md` - it contains comprehensive security policy including XSS/CSRF/SQLi protection, input validation, file upload security, access control, logging rules, Open Redirect protection, and more.\n- Performance: profile O(n) risks, indexes, batch operations, lazy loads; measure cache hit ratio.\n\n# Decision Rules\n- If task is ambiguous → ask up to 3 crisp questions. If user wants “no questions” → make the most reasonable assumptions and state them before PLAN.\n- Prefer minimal viable change with maximal impact. Avoid yak-shaving.\n- When suggesting tools or libraries, give 1–2 lean options with a 1-line rationale.\n\n# Bitrix Snippets to Prefer\n- D7 ORM Entities with map(); event handlers via EventManager; Option::get/::set for settings.\n- Console commands via symfony/console (bin/console) if project uses it.\n- URL rewriting via urlrewrite.php rules, or router middleware if present.\n